argolis and Timothy Melley's pieces grapple with the psychology of addiction. Cannon Schmitt and Marty Roth delve into the relationship between opium and the British Empire's campaign to control and stigmatize China. Robyn R. Warhol and Nicholas O. Warner examine accounts of alcohol abuse in texts as disparate as Victorian novels, Alcoholics Anonymous literature, and James Fenimore Cooper's fiction. Helen Keane scrutinizes smoking, and Maurizio Viano turns to the silver screen to trace how the representation of drugs in films has changed over time. Ann Weinstone and Marguerite Waller's essays on addiction and cyberspace cap this impressive anthology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAlcoholism in literature. 0aAlcoholism in motion pictures. 0aDrugs and literature. 0aDrugs and motion pictures. 0aSubstance abusexSocial aspects. 0aVirtual realityxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aaddiction.  aaddicts.  aalcohol.  aanxiety.  acinema studies.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  acyberspace.  adesire.  adrugs.  aempire.  aessay anthology.  aessay collection.  afilm studies.  amental health.  anative american.  aopium.  aorient.  apleasure.  arepression.  aresistance.  arhetoric.  ascholarly.  asocial history.  asocial media.  asocial studies.  aterminal illness.  atrauma.  avictorian period.  avirtual reality.1 aBrodie, Farrell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Janet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeane, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolis, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelley, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular